passages.text: BuzzMiner for Global News (X edition) (Robert Smith, PhD/Evan Hu)

In this report, we source our data from X (formerly Twitter) to run themes for the last week (Monday, 11 August, to Sunday, 17 August), using our theme mining framework, BuzzMiner. To ensure the quality of the input, we only take the content posted by selected accounts, which consist of well- known financial and non- financial institutional news outlets.

Key takeaways from the July steel production data are: 1) China's crude steel output in July remained soft, down \(4\%\) MoM / \(3\%\) YoY, but blast furnace share has grown, and pig iron output is down a more modest \(1\%\) YTD (China's apparent steel demand is down \(5\%\) YTD), 2) despite increased China steel net exports (+13% YTD), RoW steel production remains flat YTD, with India up a solid \(14\%\) YoY in July, 3) China iron ore imports are down \(2\%\) YTD, but domestic production is off \(4\%\) and port inventory is \(14\%\) (-21Mt) lower than this time last year. Steel inventory at traders and steel mills remains low. Overall, the pulse check on iron ore markets in China remains somewhat muted, with fundamentals unsupportive of material upside to prices, but cost curves acting as downside support. We view the China anti- involution trade as real, but still lacking near- term on- the- ground follow through, suggesting recent upward moves have been largely sentiment driven. Our 2026 iron ore price expectation is \(\) 95\(/t.
BHP (Lyndon Fagan) (BHP AU, OW, PT A\\(44.00)

Medium- term capex cut: Can you outline the specific projects and savings that led to the \(\) 1\(bn cut to medium- term capex guidance from\) \ \(11bn\) to \(\) 10bn\(? What do you expect an average spend rate per year medium term on equity accounted unit funding (Vicuna / Antamina / Resolution) that isn't included in capex?
Transurban (Richard Jones, CFA) (TCL AU, N, PT A\\(13.30)

Proportional Operating EBITDA was \(\) 2,848\(m, up\) 7.4\% \(on pcp and in line with our forecast of\) \ \(2,849m\) . This was driven by by \(5.4\%\) growth in Proportional Revenue and flat YoY Operating cost growth (excluding the impact of the Connect East litigation liability and restructuring costs). Traffic volumes were up \(2.2\%\) , with a strong result from the North American toll roads delivering \(6.4\%\) volume growth. Large traffic proportions slipped across Sydney, Melbourne and North America but picked up across the network in Brisbane. FY26 DPS guidance set at \(69\epsilon\) representing \(6.2\%\) growth.
Northern Star Resources Ltd. (Al Harvey) (NST AU, N, PT A\\(18.00)

KCGM Mill Expansion: The KCGM Mill Expansion is forecast to deliver \(\sim 900\) kozpa from FY29. A large step up in throughput in FY27 as the expansion cuts in of 10Mta- how confident are you in the ramp up? Can you talk to low grade stockpile displacement opportunities in the broader Kalgoorlie hub once the mill is running at nameplate 27Mta?
Pilbara Minerals Ltd. (Al Harvey) (PLS AU, UW, PT A\(\) 1.25\$

Key takeaways: 1) EBITDA of \(\) 97m\(beat our estimate by\)20\%\$ , while the underlying net loss of \(\) 88m\(was worse than our\)\\(55m\) , it did beat Street estimates of a \(\) 99m\(loss, 2) net cash of\)\\(292m\) was soft vs JPM/cons \((- 9\% / - 21\%)\) , and 3) there were limited updates on the outlook, with the company's first updated Colina resource largely unchanged vs prior owners. Overall we view the result as mixed with better EBITDA offset by softer net cash. We are Underweight rated on PLS.
CSL Limited (David Low) (CSL AU, OW, PT A\(282.00)

CSL has promised a larger cost reduction program than we expected, but the benefits will take longer and there will be almost no benefit in FY26, leading to a large cut to our forecasts (which had assumed savings). The cost- out program was overshadowed by weak results from the Behring division in 2H (attributed to the loss of tenders) and the admission that the GM will take longer to recover. While management downplayed these issues, the risk of heightened competition and sector oversupply were key investor issues, although we are less concerned on this front. The company also announced the spin- off of Seqirus, which will further muddy the waters given the complexity of the transaction. Given these concerns and the heavily second half skewed results, the near term outlook is underwhelming. However, after the price drop, we have retained our Overweight rating given the upside to our \(\) 282\(price target (previously\) \ \(305\) ).
National Storage REIT (NSR) (Richard Jones, CFA) (NSR AU, OW, PT A\(\) 2.70\$

Key takeaways: FY25 underlying earnings were \(\) 164m\(11.9cps) + 6.4\% \(on pc, marginally ahead of JPMe\) \ \(163.9m / 11.8cps\) and guidance (11.8cps). FY26 operating EPS guidance was set at set at 'minimum of 12.4cps' - implying 4.2% growth. Jun- 25 RevPAM was up \(0.4\% h / h\) to \(\) 277.3\(sqm - pleasingly this was through increased occupancy (+60bp h / h to\) 80.8\% \) as rate remained - flat h / h at \(\) 347\(sqm. Operating margins slipped for a second consecutive half to\) 69\% \(. Jun- 25 NTA increased by 5cps to\) \ \(2.58\) ps with the WACR contracting 5bp h / h to \(5.84\%\) .
Qube Holdings (Jason Steed) (QUB AU, OW, PT A\(\)4.30\$
First Take FY25: slightly below at the headline, DPS beat

Key takeaways: Overall, the result was in- line at an NPATA of \(\) 272m\(vs. JPMe at\) \ \(277m\) and consensus at \(\) 278m\(. DPS was strong at\) \ \(8.5\) ps vs. JPMe at 9.0cps and consensus at 9.3cps. Guidance points to "solid underlying earnings growth" in FY26. The uplift predominantly expected to emanate from the L&I division, benefitting from a full- year contribution from the MIRRAT acquisition. Management indicated that net finance costs will step up by \(\) 15- 20m\(on higher net debt, while capex is expected to increase to\) \ \(600 - 650m\) . Our estimates and consensus are below this guidance.
CSL Limited (David Low) (CSL AU, OW, PT A\(\)305.00\$
Our key takeaways from CSL's post- result conference call are set out below.

Ig sales hit by large "non- regrettable" tender losses. Ig sales in the June half contracted slightly, which CSL attributed to the loss of 'low margin' Ig tender contracts in the UK and Mexico. The multi- year UK contract was lost to Grifols. The head of the

Behring business quantified the loss of these contracts as removing \(3 - 4\%\) of growth they could've had in FY26, but repeated these were "non regrettable" decisions, noting the pricing was not attractive. Market share in the higher value US has remained stable with SCIg (Hizentra) still holding close to \(60\%\) market share. The management team dismissed any suggestion that the Ig market is over supplied, or that these are signs of excess plasma collections.
